A fish-eye lens might be a bit too much for a nesting box.
We learn from our mistakes.
I should have known that, given that I've already made one with a "normal" lens.
I'll tell you more about it this weekend when I've installed the second one that I made.
Let's say the birds will have a better internet connection than mine was in 2015.
Or at least, that's the goal.
The box that already contains a nesting box is taking advantage of the house's Wi-Fi.
There's still work left to connect the other one.
Okay, I hung the other nesting box during the day. Here's what it looks like in its place in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", I hear someone asking.
Up top is one of those ESP32 modules with a fish-eye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box looks strange, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2,600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a photo of the solar panel.
The gray box suspended on the side of the nesting box houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of energy.
I call that a feature. So the birds can also have a bit of intimacy.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the internet connection in our garden would be good enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to put a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and orient it downwards towards the garden.
I could still do it when I install more camera birdhouses, especially in areas far from the house, I might need it.
Now, for reasons that elude me for now, the camera is offline. It went dark just an hour after sunset.
The battery charge might have stopped three hours before sunset due to a lack of light.
Maybe it couldn't fully charge in a bit less than half a day.
I'll see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have a battery telemetry system. I might add one in a future revision.
A few more sensors would be nice, I think.
And maybe a battery that can last through the night, at least on paper.
Oh, and another lens.
The fisheye is way too much.
But I'm already looking for parts on Digikey, so I might just make a custom PCB for this purpose.
Or not. We'll see.
And it's still offline.
Great.
Considering the solar panels installed on the house, the sun is really high for only about 90 minutes.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens or not.
Still offline.
Nothing is ever simple.
Actually, on the USB-C plug I was using to connect the battery charger, the 5V and ground were reversed.
I swapped the wires, and now I have a charging indicator.
The ESP didn't connect right away, let's wait for a few minutes.
One hour later: still offline.
It seems to be restarting in a loop and triggering Tasmota's reset function.
I think the panel is just crap. I ordered a bigger one, hoping it will work.
Look what I found in the workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is so low (and partly blocked by a tree) that it drops to almost nothing as soon as I use it.
I think I'll wait until tomorrow to see if it's enough for this installation or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it should generate 12V at a maximum of 1.2A.
So either something's wrong with this panel or my multimeter, or they've changed the specs.
Good news, everyone!
They changed the specifications, and the one I have is H.S.
The titles of the old and new specifications mention a 12V, 10W panel.
That's why I don't delete my old emails.
Hey, look: the thing reconnected for about half a minute about an hour ago.
Maybe the panel charged the battery just enough for 38 seconds of energy. It would have taken a bit more than two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today. So I'm not sure if this solar panel (probably broken) will be able to generate enough energy to do anything.
Let's wait and see.
Latest update: I installed the new panel and it seems to be working.
If luck is on our side, everything will shut down at sunset, but let's wait and see.
By the way, I'm using the ping integration in Home Assistant to monitor if it's connected or not.
The round-trip time is 102 ms. Not great, but not too bad.
